To disable the use of TLS 1.0 and TLS 1.1 in ASP.NET Core with Kestrel, you need to modify the SSL protocol configuration. Here's an updated code snippet to disable TLS 1.0 and TLS 1.1:

```csharp
public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
{
    var serverOptions = app.ApplicationServices.GetRequiredService<KestrelServerOptions>();
    var sslProtocolOptions = Configuration.GetSection("SSLProtocolOptions").Get<SSLProtocolOptions>();

    if (sslProtocolOptions != null && sslProtocolOptions.SSLProtocolVersions != null && sslProtocolOptions.SSLProtocolVersions.Length > 0)
    {
        var protocolsToEnable = sslProtocolOptions.SSLProtocolVersions
            .Select(v => Enum.Parse<Microsoft.AspNetCore.Server.Kestrel.Https.HttpsProtocols>(v, ignoreCase: true))
            .ToList();

        // Disable TLS 1.0 and TLS 1.1
        protocolsToEnable.Remove(HttpsProtocols.Tls10);
        protocolsToEnable.Remove(HttpsProtocols.Tls11);

        serverOptions.ConfigureHttpsDefaults(listenOptions =>
        {
            listenOptions.UseHttps(httpsOptions =>
            {
                httpsOptions.SslProtocols = protocolsToEnable;
            });
        });
    }

    // Other configurations...

    app.UseRouting();
    // Other middleware and endpoints...
}
```

In this updated code:
1. We create a list `protocolsToEnable` to store the SSL protocols to be enabled.
2. We remove `HttpsProtocols.Tls10` and `HttpsProtocols.Tls11` from the list to disable TLS 1.0 and TLS 1.1 respectively.
3. The updated list of protocols is then assigned to `httpsOptions.SslProtocols` within `listenOptions.UseHttps`.

Remember to update your configuration file accordingly to specify the SSL protocol versions you want to enable. When you remove TLS 1.0 and TLS 1.1 from the list, only TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3 will be enabled, assuming your system supports these newer protocols.

