To use AES encryption instead of 3DES for SSL/TLS in an ASP.NET Core web service, you need to configure the SSL/TLS cipher suites to include AES-based cipher suites. Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

```csharp
public static IHostBuilder CreateHostBuilder(string[] args) =>
    Host.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
        .ConfigureWebHostDefaults(webBuilder =>
        {
            webBuilder.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
            {
                options.ConfigureHttpsDefaults(httpsOptions =>
                {
                    httpsOptions.SslProtocols = SslProtocols.Tls12;
                    httpsOptions.CipherSuitesPolicy = new CipherSuitesPolicy()
                        .SetCipherSuites(
                            CipherSuites.TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384,
                            CipherSuites.TLS_ECDHE_RSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384
                        );
                });
            });

            webBuilder.UseStartup<Startup>();
        });
```

In this code:

1. We configure the Kestrel server options using `webBuilder.ConfigureKestrel`.
2. Within the `ConfigureHttpsDefaults` method, we set the desired SSL/TLS protocol version (in this case, `SslProtocols.Tls12`).
3. We create a new `CipherSuitesPolicy` and set the desired AES-based cipher suites using the `SetCipherSuites` method. The example includes two cipher suites: `TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384` and `TLS_ECDHE_RSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384`. You can add more or remove them based on your requirements.

Please note that the availability of cipher suites may depend on the operating system, .NET Core version, and cryptographic libraries installed on the system. Ensure that the chosen cipher suites are supported by your target environment.

